Like so many other irresponsible rulers, the ‘ decemviri legibus scribundis' were corrupted by the taste of power which they had enjoyed3 so much did they relish it that they attempted to make their own office permanent, and to revolutionise the form of government by substituting themselves entirely for the consuls and tribunes. Pre- tending to make an ‘ exaequatio iuris ’ the main object of their policy, they set to work to attain it by reactionary measures; they were for retaining the comitia curiata only for religious purposes, and for abolishing the comitia tributa altogether ς thus the plebeians would lose their organization, and so their very existence as an order, while the privileges os the patricians would be perpetuated, though under · forms slightly altered or disguised. The plebs saw through the design, and (s. c. 449) resorted once again to the well-tried stratagem of a secession. The patrician opposition at once crumbled to no- thing, and the old constitution, with its consuls and tn'bunes, was restored.
